Raw Data Breakdown:
Title: The title of the article or news piece (e.g., "Donald Trump Might Soon Be Vying for Presidency While Facing Criminal Charges | Vanity Fair").
Snippet: A brief summary or excerpt of the content (e.g., "Donald Trump is making moves towards another presidential bid despite ongoing criminal investigations...").
URL: The link to the full article on the publisher's website.
Image: The URL to an associated image (usually a thumbnail or relevant image).
Source: The name of the publication or website providing the article.
Published Date: The date when the article was published.
How It's Processed:
Once this raw data is retrieved, I then parse it into a more structured format (like JSON) by extracting key pieces of information—such as titles, URLs, images, and sources—and organizing them into categories.

For example:

Titles go under "title".
Links to Articles go under "url".
Images go under "image".
Published dates are noted as "published_date".
The data is cleaned up, and irrelevant or redundant information is discarded so that the results are more digestible and useful for you.

Does this give you a better idea of how the data is structured before parsing?

